<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Saving and Borrowing): Tempting the tepid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OLIVE THOMPSON, Moneyfacts and CHRISTINE BAYLISS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lenders have been offering gifts in various guises all year to tempt the
lukewarm house-buyer. Indeed, by abolishing mortgage indemnity premiums
(Mips), Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester might have thought it was offering the
ultimate gift. Yet, this is of real interest only to those with a small
deposit, writes Olive Thompson of Moneyfacts.
Moreover, although radical (in that it applies to all mortgages), it is not
an entirely new initiative. Leeds and Holbeck waive the premium on their
new, discounted, variable-rate deals for first-time buyers.
Other lenders which do not charge Mips on specific products include Portman,
Skipton, Melton Mowbray, Citibank, Bank of Ireland Home Mortgages, Homeloans
Direct, Legal &amp; General, The Mortgage Business and UCB.
Some lenders are more flexible than others where premiums are concerned.
Northern Rock now allows them to be added to the loan, as do Yorkshire BS
and Lambeth, but Greenwich and Derbyshire insist on the payment up-front.
Increasing the debt could be the easy option, but do not overlook the fact
that interest will be charged - and can mount up - if the premium is not
paid off during the first year of the mortgage.
Cash rebates can be particularly useful to a first-time buyer to offset the
cost of Mips, which could be Pounds 880 on a property valued at Pounds
55,000, with a 5 per cent deposit.
The Pounds 1,000 rebate offered by Chelsea is for advances over Pounds
40,000 - for advances up to and including Pounds 40,000, the rebate is
Pounds 500.
Fixed-rate mortgages for three years can still be found at less than the
standard variable rate. The Woolwich recently reduced its two-year fixed
rate by 1 per cent to 7.49 per cent.
Longer-term fixes may be attractive for those who want peace of mind: the
TSB has revised its five-year fixed rate down by 0.24 per cent to a
comparative 8.95 per cent.
Although the majority of banks and building societies have increased their
savings rates following September's base rate rise, a number still have not
passed on the benefits to their investors, writes Christine Bayliss. The
Scarborough has actually cut rates by 0.5 per cent on its Scarborough '94
account.
Fixed-rate products - both flat and escalating rates - continue to be
popular. Indeed, the demand has been such that bonds from the Chelsea and
West Bromwich were available for only a short time before being withdrawn.
Rates of around the 8 per cent mark are available for two to four years. The
highest comes from the Confederation Bank: 9 per cent for five years.
Offshore institutions have, in the main, also followed events onshore. With
higher balances, they often pay more, the bonus being that the interest is
paid gross. While it is taxable and must be declared by UK residents, the
interest received can be re-invested for maximum benefit until the tax bill
is due. In some cases, it is possible for investors to choose when the
interest is paid to make maximum use of this advantage.
</TEXT>
<XX>
