<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Investing for Income): Gilt issues - best
value v tax status
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
All gilts with a fixed redemption date have two yields. The current
yield (also known as the interest yield) relates the coupon to the
current share price and tells you what your current income is. The
redemption yield also takes account of the capital gain - or loss - you
can expect to make if you hold the stock until redemption in order to
calculate your total return. Our table shows that total return net of
income tax for different types of taxpayer. Your capital gain on a gilt
 -a UK government bond - is tax free. However, you pay tax on the
interest. Therefore, gilts which deliver a higher proportion of their
total return as capital gain are more tax efficient, and - other things
being equal - more attractive to higher rate taxpayers.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
