<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): A classic case of risk and reward
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors have traditionally fared well in UK privatisations. There have
been a few notable exceptions, as shareholders in British Steel can testify,
but the vast majority of companies sold off by the state in the past 10
years have seen their shares outperform the market, some by a considerable
margin.
What, then, should investors make of the opportunity that will soon arise to
invest in the UK coal industry when it is privatised later this year?
British Coal is no ordinary privatisation. The government has conducted most
sell-offs by putting a price on the assets and then floating the company,
complete with management, on the stock market at an appropriate price. Coal
is being sold differently, in part because it is seen as being a risky
business. Ministers thought asking institutions and small investors to
subscribe might lead to trouble and decided instead on a 'trade sale' to
existing companies.
Last month, RJB Mining emerged as the government's preferred choice for the
three English regions of British Coal. These comprise 15 of the 16 remaining
operating deep mines and account for more than 85 per cent of UK coal
production.
RJB is, however, a relatively small company. Whereas it is capitalised on
the stock exchange at less than Pounds 160m, it needs to raise up to Pounds
1.05bn to finance its Pounds 914m bid. Outside investors will be able to
take part because RJB, advised by Barclays de Zoete Wedd, plans to raise up
to Pounds 425m through issuing shares.
Institutional investors, including pension funds, will be the prime target
but RJB is planning to set aside 5 per cent of shares for an offer for sale
in which retail (private) investors will be asked to subscribe. This will
rise to 15 per cent if demand is high enough.
Investors should not expect an advertising campaign along the lines of the
'Tell Sid' strategy which accompanied British Gas's move into the private
sector. RJB's share offer will be for the 'sophisticated' investor - often,
a euphemism for the rich. Stockbrokers are likely to advise clients that no
one should put their last pennies and pounds into RJB.
The company, led by chief executive Richard Budge, has a good track record
in spite of its association with AF Budge, the engineering company from
which it emerged two years ago shortly before that company went into
receivership. RJB is well respected in the mining industry, where it made
its name largely as an opencast operator.
Its problem - or potential problem - is the speed of its growth. Last year
was its first year as a quoted company and it made pre-tax profits of Pounds
12m on turnover of Pounds 75m. Assuming it completes its British Coal
acquisitions, RJB expects to be making Pounds 220m annually on sales of
Pounds 1.2bn by the end of the century.
It is this confidence that enabled the company to offer at least 50 per cent
more than the nearest rival for the English coal regions. But some analysts
and quite a few executives in both the coal and electricity sectors believe
RJB has over-stretched itself.
RJB's assumptions on the size of future coal markets, and the prices at
which it can sell, are at the top of industry expectations. Even its
'conservative case' calculations are regarded as ambitious by coal analysts,
including McCloskey Coal Information.
RJB is offering handsome rewards for shareholders who are prepared to wait a
few years. The expected dividend yield starts at 4.5 per cent in the first
year, about the market average, but RJB is promising a policy of rapid
dividend growth with 'substantial increases' after debt is reduced.
The company expects virtually all debt to be paid off by 1998. But with up
to Pounds 528m of borrowings needed, the company's critics think that is far
too optimistic. Some are predicting RJB could get into financial trouble.
Potential investors will have a chance to make their own minds up when the
pathfinder prospectus for the share issue comes out in the next few days. It
will be a classic case of deciding whether the rich rewards on offer are
worth the perceived risk of investing.
