<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): Vodafone's crime bill - Company
in the News
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The IBM executive neglected his lunch as he recounted, sourly, how his
cellular telephone had been ripped from his car by a bicycle-mounted thief
in south London. He had become another victim in a crime wave in which
15,000 such phones are stolen every month.
Vodafone, the UK market leader in mobile phones, can count itself a victim
of the same phenomenon. Its interim results this week showed profits in the
first half of the year were dented by fraud and criminal activity at home.
Abroad, it was held back by heavier than expected start-up costs, amounting
to Pounds 40m in the half year. Nevertheless, it managed to come in ahead of
most analysts' estimates, with pre-tax profits of Pounds 186.4m on sales of
Pounds 560.7m compared with predictions of Pounds 175m to Pounds 185m.
One reason for Vodafone's success is that the market for mobile phones has
expanded beyond all expectations in the past year. The growth has favoured
mainly the established companies, Vodafone and Cellnet, offering mature and
proven analogue systems, over newcomers Mercury One-2-One and Orange. Their
digital networks cover less of the country and still have performance
problems.
This Christmas should see an unprecedented boom in mobile phone sales.
Looking further ahead, analysts think there could be 10m subscribers to
cellular services by 2000 compared with estimates of 8m a year ago.
Vodafone's share of the growth over the past year was 263,000, an increase
of 140 per cent over the same period last year. But the expansion in numbers
brought an increase in fraud and 'low-quality' subscribers - people who take
the service with no intention of paying and must eventually be disconnected.
'Phantom' subscribers, signed up by unscrupulous dealers to secure
commissions, and 're-chippers' - people who alter the electrical identity of
portable phones to make calls at other subscribers' expense  - have added to
the problems.
The cost to the company of various forms of fraud is about 1 per cent of
turnover. Indeed, Vodafone has been making clear to analysts that the
problems of fraud and low-quality subscribers have not been eliminated
fully, and that low numbers of net connections compared with the rival
Cellnet are expected to continue for the next two months.
Abroad, Vodafone's businesses in Hong Kong and Malta are profitable while
Greece and South Africa have performed well. It also belongs to a
consortium, led by Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, which leads in the battle to get a
mobile telephony licence in Spain.
A big question for Vodafone and its competitors is how long prices can
remain stable. They have held up strongly over the past year, helped by the
declaration in June by chief executive Gerry Whent that Vodafone would not
cut its tariffs this year.
Inevitably, however, they will fall. And, at the same time, much of the new
growth is coming from the residential sector - which is inherently less
profitable than the business market.
</TEXT>
