<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): New issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK investors applying for shares in BSkyB, the satellite broadcasting group,
will be able to specify a price level beyond which they do not want to go,
writes David Blackwell. Applications will be based on the amount of money
people want to invest, rather than on the number of shares, as the price
will not be decided until December 8 - the day dealings start. The minimum
investment is Pounds 500.
Yesterday, the group launched its UK retail offer of 36.4m shares, part of
the global offer of 343m. They will be priced somewhere between 233p and
268p, and the allocations will be decided after the offer closes on December
6.
The price range gives the group a valuation between Pounds 4bn and Pounds
4.6bn.
Twelve share shops where investors can register have been established at
various high street banks and institutions. There will also be application
forms in the national press.
Earlier this week, the flotation of Telewest Communications indicated strong
interest by investors in broadcasting - the offer was six times subscribed.
The shares were priced at 182p on Wednesday, valuing the group at Pounds
1.8bn.
Telewest, a 50-50 joint venture between TCI of Denver, the largest US cable
operator, and US West, the regional telephone company, will be the first UK
cable company to join the London Stock Exchange. Dealing is expected to
begin in London and the Nasdaq exchange in New York on Wednesday.
Research Machines, a supplier of computers and computer software to schools
and colleges, said on Thursday that it was coming to the market not to raise
money but to raise its profile. The group, relatively unknown outside the UK
education market, is making a placing likely to value it at about Pounds
30m.
On Monday, Samax, which is developing mines in Africa, postponed its float
until early next year. It had planned to raise Pounds 16m by the end of this
month via a placing by stockbrokers Credit Lyonnais Laing, on terms that
would have valued the company at about Pounds 50m. Samax blamed adverse
conditions in the new issues market.
</TEXT>
