<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money: What is a share option?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A share option is a right to acquire shares in the future at a price which
is usually fixed when the option is granted, writes David Cohen. Virtually
every big UK company has an approved 'executive' scheme under which the
directors and chosen executives can receive an option over shares worth up
to four times their salary.
The price payable when such an option is 'exercised' - that is, converted
into shares - will generally be the share price at the grant date.
There is a set period during which options can be exercised, at the end of
which they expire. Exercising options more than three years but less than 10
after the grant date gives some tax advantages.
Suppose, say, that you are head-hunted to be finance director of a quoted
company at a salary of Pounds 150,000, and that you are also promised a
four-times-salary share option. The option is granted in November 1994 when
the share price is Pounds 2.
You will, therefore, have the right to buy 300,000 shares (Pounds 150,000 x
4 / 2) any time between 1998 and 2004.
If your prime aim is to make as much money as possible out of your option -
rather than to become a shareholder in your employer - you will wait until
you think the share price has peaked. Then you will buy the shares and sell
them immediately.
The profit you make will be highly sensitive to movements in the share
price. For example, while a sale price of Pounds 2.40 will net you Pounds
120,000 (40p x 300,000), a price rise of a further 10 per cent to Pounds
2.60 will boost your windfall by 50 per cent to Pounds 180,000 (60p x
300,000). This gearing effect is, of course, characteristic of traded
options and other 'derivative' instruments.
The real joy of executive options is that there is no risk of losing money.
Having paid nothing for his right, the executive will exercise it only if he
can do so profitably. If he cannot, he simply ditches it or allows it to
lapse.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P874  Management and Public Relations.
    P6733 Trusts, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-7105</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EK0AOAAWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941126
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money: Executive gluttony under attack - Fury over
British Gas pay rises is fuelling demands for change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Part of the price British Gas directors are paying for their spectacular pay
increases is the scrapping of 'automatic' share option grants. But the
context for this apparent sacrifice is a growing consensus that the options
gravy train is in danger of hitting the buffers.
Executives aboard this financial express have had a very satisfactory ride,
but shareholders and the public have felt increasingly that they were being
taken for a ride.
It is a truth universally acknowledged, that the raison d'etre of share
incentives is to motivate executives, so boosting corporate performance.
Shareholders may see their slice of the cake reduced because extra shares
are issued to managers - but they will be better off if they are compensated
for that reduction by the cake-expanding skills of those same managers.
Critics of conventional share options question whether the behaviour of a
company's share price is the best indicator of the performance of its senior
executives. Overall stock market conditions will exert a strong influence on
most companies' prices. The boss of a company which excels in a bear market
could still be left with worthless options; by contrast, those whose
companies perform indifferently during a bull phase will, usually, be
rewarded.
The anomaly can be even more glaring where a whole sector has outperformed.
Which of the electricity overlords would have the chutzpah to claim the
credit for the more-than-threefold increase in all the Regional Electricity
Companies' (recs) share prices since privatisation? Yet, those increases
have been the sole basis for those executives' vast options gains.
One solution is to prevent options from being exercised unless, during the
option period, the share price meets a relative performance target. This
could be beating the FT-SE index or coming in the top half or quartile in
the company's own sector. The option-holder's actual gain would still
reflect the absolute price movement, but receiving that gain would depend on
whether the relative hurdle had been cleared.
To extend this argument: if the objective is to reward executives who do
well for their shareholders, then options should be linked to total
shareholder return. This would encompass not just share price growth but
also the value of dividends received during the option period.
It seems that this concept of overall return is to be the linchpin of the
new British Gas executive share option scheme. The peer group against which
performance is to be measured will be the companies making up the FT-SE 100
index.
There is, however, a widespread feeling that the inadequacy of share prices
as a yardstick of performance cannot be cured simply by tagging on a
relative target. Instead, it is argued, the benchmark of success should be
management's ability to enhance earnings per share.
Options should be realisable only if EPS growth beats a target. This can be
by reference to the average EPS increase of other companies - constituents
of an index or companies in the same sector - or linked to an external
variable such as the retail prices index. Each of these alternative
approaches has its strengths and weaknesses, and each can produce arbitrary
results. Let us revert for a moment to the electricity companies.
All had embarrassingly large cash mountains which they have been shrinking
either by paying extraordinary dividends to shareholders or buying back
their own shares. No doubt a good corporate case can be made out for either
alternative. Yet, a super-dividend will work immediate wonders for overall
shareholder return but do nothing at all for EPS, while a buy-back will have
precisely the opposite effect.
The British Gas share option scheme has no performance conditions. Indeed,
one of the justifications being suggested for the huge increases in basic
salaries is that the executives are sacrificing 'automatic' option gains for
a much riskier performance-related alternative.
Yet, Gas is hardly alone in making this switch. Hundreds of quoted companies
have revamped their incentives by introducing performance criteria in recent
years.
Is this the result of board members developing guilty consciences after
raking in easy winnings for so long? A more plausible explanation is that
companies have been responding to a statement in July 1993 by the
Association of British Insurers and the National Association of Pension
Funds.
This called for all executive options to be subject to targets requiring
'sustained and significant improvement in underlying financial performance'.
Since insurance companies and pension funds are by far the most influential
blocs of shareholders in quoted companies, few have stood out against this
institutional diktat. And since the main motivation has been to appease the
institutions, the specific targets selected have, predictably, tended to
follow the wishes of the ABI, the more assertive of the powerful twins. So,
most companies have plumped for a target of EPS growth beating the average
rate for comparable companies, or exceeding RPI increases by at least 2 per
cent a year.
In spite of these improvements, some still see the concept of share options
as fundamentally flawed. Special criticism is directed at the high gearing
effect which magnifies and distorts the impact of share price movement. This
has prompted several major plcs - although not, apparently, British Gas - to
replace their option schemes with long-term incentive plans which deliver
free shares to executives provided they stay put for a set period (usually
five years) and their company meets pre-determined performance targets
(usually similar to those now being set for option schemes).
Meanwhile, the Labour party has put Revenue-approved options high on its
tax-avoidance hit list and has vowed to treat option gains as income rather
than capital. All in all, it does seem clear that top directors probably
should hedge their bets by buying some lottery tickets.
David Cohen is a partner in the City law firm of Paisner &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P874  Management and Public Relations.
    P6733 Trusts, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
