<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 94 / Weekend Money: The Budget and you - Scheherazade Daneshkhu
ponders what the chancellor has in store
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Life will become more expensive for most people from April because of tax
increases already scheduled from the last Budget (see left). Some
concessions have been given to the elderly, such as an increase in the
married couple's allowance for those aged 65 and over and help with fuel
bills - but there is room for more.
What can savers and investors expect when Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
stands up on Tuesday? Can they expect a reprieve - or to be hit for more?
Clarke has not held out much hope of tax cuts saying these would be
premature but, with the next general election only two to three years away,
he might try to engineer some kind of 'feel-good' factor. Some of the
analysts' predictions are listed on the right. Clarke could decide to help
the long-term unemployed and working parents, perhaps by lowering National
Insurance contributions for companies giving work to the former, and tax
relief on child-care costs for the latter.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
TUESDAY'S NEWS
The sugar coating
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Self assessment
More legislation on tax self-assessment, scheduled for 1996-97
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Income tax
Lower 20 per cent band likely to be widened from first Pounds 3,000 to
Pounds 3,500 or more
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Personal allowances
Single person's allowance of Pounds 3,445, frozen for past two years,
may be raised with inflation. Married couple's allowance for under 65s
likely to be restricted to 10 per cent from April 1996
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
National Insurance
Legislation likely to stop employers avoiding NICs by paying bonuses
in kind. NICs and income tax could be more integrated
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Saving and investment
Tessa tax-free deposit accounts begin maturing January 1996. Possible
extension to seven years or new tax-free personal equity plans (Peps)
may be capped. Optimists think rules may be simplified
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Capital gains tax/inheritance tax
Thresholds may be raised. Simplification of CGT possible
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Pensions
Personal pension holders may be given flexibility about when they buy
their annuity. Possible plans to raise tax from pensions
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Venture capital
Detail expected on venture capital trusts, designed to encourage
investment in smallest start-up companies. Possible changes to make
Enterprise Investment Scheme more attractive
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Smoking and drinking
Duty on tobacco already scheduled for 3 per cent increase after
inflation but might go up by even more. Beer and wine could escape
increased duties to ease cross-Channel price differences
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Cars
Road fuel duties due to rise by 5 per cent next year but could be higher
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Surprises
Housing: Hopes for good news to cheer lacklustre housing market. Needed
to balance possible moves to restrict mortgage interest tax relief to
10 per cent from April 1996
Tax relief: Possible new form of tax relief, perhaps a deduction in cost
of childcare or relief for train and bus season tickets
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
