<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / International Company News: Torras files debt proposals to
lift receivership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Grupo Torras, the Kuwait Investment Office's investment arm in Spain, has
filed a payment proposal to 3,369 creditors aimed at lifting a two-year old
receivership, Reuter reports from Madrid.
The proposal offers 97 per cent of debts owed to small creditors of Torras,
while creditors related to KIO are being offered just over 10 per cent.
The debt owed by Grupo Torras to KIO-related companies accounts for 93.5 per
cent of total debt to unsecured creditors which amounted to Pta219.87bn
(Dollars 1.69bn) when it suspended payments. Of this, Pta205.45bn was owed
to KIO.
A source close to the negotiations said the proposal implies KIO-related
companies taking a write-down of Pta184.45bn, just less than 90 per cent of
Torras's debt to them. The total payments Grupo Torras would make under the
plan was Pta27.73bn.
The deadline for creditors to respond is January 21 1995. A creditors'
committee will be set up, comprising two creditors, a representative of the
company and two from the receivers.
Grupo Torras filed for receivership in December 1992, in spite of the KIO
injecting Pta338bn into the group in the preceding 30 months.
Torras said the receivership report confirmed that part of this capital was
provided by the KIO during the Gulf war, contradicting claims by former
management that it was channelled back to Kuwait and left the group
decapitalised.
KIO filed suit in Madrid in January 1993 against its former agent in Spain,
Mr Javier de la Rosa, the Catalan financier, as well as seven other former
KIO and Torras executives. Mr De la Rosa is in jail facing separate charges
of fraud in his Grand Tibidabo leisure group.
In its suit, KIO-Torras said the former executives, who resigned in
mid-1992, were responsible through fraud and misrepresenting accounts for
losses of Dollars 1bn and that KIO's Dollars 5bn investment in Spain had
been squandered. The case is still before the Spanish courts.
Torras said KIO financial backing had been crucial in avoiding a collapse in
its Spanish investments, pointing to Pta102bn for paper company Torraspapel,
chemicals group Ercros, real estate firm Prima Inmobiliaria and Industrias
Bures between May-December 1992. It said following agreement with the
Spanish government in early 1993, KIO committed to injecting Dollars 20m
into Torraspapel. In April that year, Torras capitalised its Pta23.5bn debt
with Torraspapel.
With a loan of Pta14.8bn from the state Instituto de Credito Oficial, yet to
be authorised, and Pta3.5bn in working capital earmarked by the KIO between
1993 and 1994, it said Torraspapel was on the way to recovery.
</TEXT>
