<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / International Company News: BASF sees further strong growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BASF, the German chemicals group, expects a 50 per cent increase in pre-tax
earnings to DM1.6bn (Dollars 1.03bn) this year, after profits more than
trebled in the third quarter.
Forecasting further growth for the coming two years, Mr Jurgen Strube,
chairman, said he expected his main objective - a 10 per cent return on
capital - to be achieved in 1996. After that, he was counting on less
pronounced expansion and increased competition in the closing years of the
decade.
Mr Strube yesterday announced a 99 per cent rise in earnings for the first
nine months, to DM1.2bn, on sales up 7.6 per cent at DM32.4bn.
Although the sharpness of the recovery was gratifying, he said he was not
satisfied with profitability, and would press on with cost reductions. This
would entail a further 4,000 job losses during 1995, following more cuts in
the current year.
Mr Strube said fixed costs had been cut by DM1.4bn in the past three years,
and further economies worth DM100m had been made in the nine months to the
end of September. Group payroll costs in the review period had fallen 3.3
per cent.
He said the company would reinforce its less cyclical businesses - including
pharmaceuticals, natural gas, plant protection and fine chemicals - as he
noted continuing pressure on producer prices while raw material costs
continued to rise.
Pharmaceuticals sales are expected to rise by a third to DM3bn when
negotiations to buy the drugs operations of Boots, the UK group, are
concluded.
Mr Strube said he expected the talks to be completed by the end of the year,
and be followed by an integration programme. Apart from the geographical
synergies between the two groups' drugs operations, he said Boots' blood
pressure and diabetes treatments were especially interesting. Addressing
workers' concerns over possible job losses, he said adjustments would be
required on all sides.
According to an interim report published yesterday, operating profits rose
in all divisions except oil and gas, although earnings were once again
reduced by extraordinary items, especially write-offs of plastics, fibres
and consumer products plant in the US.
North American sales rose 3 per cent in the review period and, while
European sales increased 8.5 per cent, turnover in Germany fell 0.6 per
cent. Asian, Australian and African sales showed the strongest growth, up 12
per cent.
</TEXT>
