<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / UK Company News: Chamberlain Phipps rises fourfold in maiden
interims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chamberlain Phipps, the shoe components and footwear group, reported maiden
interim results showing a fourfold increase in pre-tax profits, and
announced its first acquisition since it returned to the market in August.
Pre-tax profits for the six months to October 1 jumped from Pounds 1.05m to
Pounds 4.5m, on turnover doubled from Pounds 32.2m to Pounds 66.6m. The
profits figure included an Pounds 800,000 reorganisation charge and, for the
first time, results from Chamberlain's French operations bought just over a
year ago.
Mr Dan Sullivan, the US-born chairman, said that, on a like-for-like basis,
pre-tax profits for the half-year rose by about 21 per cent to just over
Pounds 5m. Sales on a like-for-like basis, excluding disposals, had been
flat.
The materials division, which includes the footwear components business
formerly owned by Evode, improved operating profits from Pounds 1.32m to
Pounds 1.62m, on sales 23 per cent down at Pounds 19.6m. Mr Sullivan said
trading in the UK continued to be difficult, although the division had
enjoyed strong export growth of about 15 per cent.
The footwear business, including SAC and Thierry which were not consolidated
into the group's results at flotation, increased operating profits from
Pounds 391,000 to Pounds 4.19m. Sales jumped from Pounds 6.59m to Pounds
47m.
Chamberlain also announced a conditional agreement to acquire Ouest Parts,
the largest supplier of components to the French shoe industry, for about
FFr74m (Pounds 8.79m) in cash. Last year the group returned profits of about
Pounds 1.4m and had net assets of about Pounds 2.2m. Mr Sullivan said he
expected to expand further in continental Europe, and Chamberlain was
currently in discussions about a second purchase.
Chamberlain finished the first half with net debt representing almost 90 per
cent of shareholders' funds. This was expected to fall to about 60 per cent
by the year-end.
The group declared a maiden dividend of 2.7p. Earnings rose from 6.7p to
7.9p. On a pro forma basis earnings rose to 7.7p.
Chamberlain's shares, floated at 165p in August, closed 3p up at 183p.
</TEXT>
