<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / UK Company News: VSEL shareholders resolve to keep 'playing
fields level'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Financial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shareholders in VSEL, the nuclear submarine builder which is the subject of
competing bids from GEC and British Aerospace, last night voted unanimously
for a resolution enabling GEC to buy more than 15 per cent of its shares -
but only if and when an unconditional offer from the company is accepted by
a majority of VSEL shareholders, writes Our Financial Staff.
The resolution, passed at an egm, was similar to one passed which allows BAe
to acquire more than 15 per cent if its offer is accepted. VSEL chairman
Lord Chalfont said the latest move was an enabling measure to keep the
playing fields level.
Lord Chalfont said his company was still advising shareholders to take no
action over either bid until competition issues are settled by the Office of
Fair Trading.
He said he hoped that a simultaneous decision on whether to refer bids to
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission would be taken by December 7.
Shareholders are awaiting a response from GEC to the revised Pounds 573m bid
made for VSEL by BAe last Friday, topping GEC's bid by Pounds 41m.
</TEXT>
