<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / UK Company News: Quadramatic maintains its programme with
Kestrel deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Quadramatic, the coin-handling and optical group which came to market in
July 1993, has continued its promised programme of acquisitions with the
purchase of Kestrel Injection Moulders, a maker of precision plastic
injection mouldings, for up to Pounds 6.65m.
At the time of the flotation, Mr Tony Gartland, chairman, said he wanted to
build a specialist engineering group by acquisition.
The initial net cash consideration for Kestrel is Pounds 4.4m, after the
Pounds 1m sale and leaseback of a Kestrel freehold property to certain of
its vendors. An additional deferred amount of up to Pounds 2.25m, in cash or
shares, is profits-related.
Plymouth-based Kestrel made pre-tax profits of Pounds 855,000 on Pounds
4.19m turnover in the year ended May 31. In the six months to March,
Quadramatic made pre-tax profits of Pounds 3.72m on turnover of Pounds
17.6m. Quadramatic's flotation was followed in November 1993 by the Pounds
11.25m acquisition of Quota, a private holding company for two high-tech
businesses.
Mr Glenn Powers, finance director, said originally the group wanted four
divisions - hence its name - but that now the building of an equally
weighted three was going well. Coin handling remained the biggest, followed
by instruments and then plastic moulding.
The group would think about a fourth when the market capitalisation
approached the Pounds 150m mark. The shares rose 3p yesterday to 168p for a
valuation of about Pounds 66.5m.
</TEXT>
