<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Mexican setback for Allied Domecq: Further progress expected
in second half from Spanish purchase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Allied Domecq, the drinks and retailing group, reported a 16.5 per cent rise
in interim pre-tax profits to Pounds 310m despite a setback in the Mexican
spirits market.
With spirits, wine and retailing showing only marginal growth overall,
financial items accounted for almost all the rise in profits from Pounds
266m a year earlier. Finance charges fell by Pounds 20m to Pounds 80m while
disposals brought a Pounds 2m profit against a loss of Pounds 21m a year
ago.
Trading profits rose Pounds 1m to Pounds 388m on turnover up 5.5 per cent at
Pounds 2.87bn. Mr Tony Hales, chief executive, said the group would make
further progress in the second half thanks to underlying growth and a full
contribution from Domecq, the Spanish drinks group Allied acquired earlier
this year for Pounds 809m.
Domecq, which contributed two months' trading profits to the first half,
suffered a 5 per cent fall in sales volumes in Mexico because of political
and economic uncertainty. Allied said the local market should recover next
year. In contrast, Domecq's Spanish volumes rose 13 per cent. Integration of
Domecq into the group was going well, the company said.
Trading profits from Allied's existing spirits and wines businesses rose
Pounds 1m to Pounds 153m. In the UK, Teacher's whisky, Beefeater gin and
Harveys sherry increased market shares.
Retailing profits rose Pounds 5m to Pounds 118m with underlying profits up
5.4 per cent. Return from leased pubs were flat but managed pubs' profits
were up 6 per cent. Drink sales rose 5 per cent and food sales 20 per cent.
Profits at Victoria Wine, the off-licence chain, were up 35 per cent thanks
to the acquisition of Augustus Barnett but only 1 per cent without its
inclusion.
In the US, like-for-like sales at Dunkin' Donuts grew 4 per cent and at
Baskin-Robbins, the ice cream chain, by 1.5 per cent.
Profits at Carlsberg-Tetley, the group's UK brewing joint venture with
Carlsberg, the Danish brewer, fell 9 per cent. Its beer volumes rose 1.5 per
cent while the UK market slipped 0.5 per cent. Margins were hurt by
discounting and growth of the lower margin take-home trade.
'We are looking for stability rather than profit growth' at the joint
venture, said Mr Hales.
The board declared an interim dividend of 7.75p a share, up 6.2 per cent.
Earnings per share were 18p against 14.8p including the exceptional items or
17.8p against 17.1p without. The group is changing its year-end to August
31, effective next year.
</TEXT>
