<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Tory MPs advise on trade with Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, WILLIAM LEWIS and JAMES WHITTINGTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two Conservative MPs, including the parliamentary assistant to Mr Malcolm
Rifkind, defence secretary, have been advising a commercial lobby group
which wants to increase trade between Iraq and the UK.
The two are Mr Henry Bellingham, parliamentary private secretary to Mr
Rifkind, and Mr Michael Colvin, chairman of the Conservative foreign affairs
committee.
They have been advising the Iraqi British Interests (IBI) Group - a lobby
association which in August organised one of the first British trade
delegations to Baghdad since the Gulf war. Sanctions were imposed on Iraq in
August 1990 after the invasion of Kuwait. 'They have advised us on who to
speak to in Whitehall if we want to seek advice on how to avoid breaking
United Nations sanctions, how would we do so,' said Mr Edmund Sykes,
secretary of the IBI. Mr Bellingham said: 'I have no regular contacts with
the IBI.' Mr Colvin was unavailable for comment.
Some 34 British and European companies will exhibit in Baghdad next week in
an attempt to win contracts from the Iraqi government. Companies from
Germany, France, Austria, Spain and Britain involved in the health and water
treatment sectors will exhibit at two trade fairs in Baghdad organised from
the UK by Orient Exhibitions, a Kent-based company.
Mr Andrew Maclean, one of Orient's directors, said communication licences,
issued by the Department of Trade and Industry, had been obtained by 17 UK
concerns, enabling them to talk directly to the Iraqis.
Mr Maclean said the companies attending the fair included Zeneca, the
pharmaceutical group; Weir Pumps, the Glasgow-based engineering group; and
Johnson &amp; Johnson, a leading supplier of medical products.
'Iraq has been a major market in the past and we are confident it will be in
the future. We want to be in position when sanctions are lifted,' said Sir
Ron Garrick, managing director and chief executive of the Weir Group.
Mr Stephen Crouch, the IBI's director-general, travelled to Jordan in
September, with Mr Bellingham, the MP for Norfolk North West. The MP had an
informal meeting with a senior official from the Iraqi foreign ministry on
September 3.
Mr Bellingham said the visit 'was a private visit paid for by myself as a
backbench MP'. He was not told that he would be meeting the Iraqi official
at a social engagement. He informed officials from the Foreign Office and
Ministry of Defence of the meeting. 'They were grateful that I'd informed
them,' he said.
In a letter obtained by the Financial Times, Mr Crouch states that with Mr
Bellingham he had meetings with a number of Jordanian government officials
and that 'we also met with a delegation from the Iraqi Ministry of Foreign
Affairs in order to listen to their point of view'.
'Where have you been', Page 7
</TEXT>
