<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / CBI price survey adds to rate rise pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The proportion of manufacturers planning to increase prices rose again this
month, according to the latest Confederation of British Industry monthly
trends survey, renewing fears of inflationary pressures.
Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England, has in the past paid
particular attention to the CBI prices findings, and today's result will
fuel speculation that the governor will press for an early rise in base
rates when he meets Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, on December 7.
However, the CBI survey did find that manufacturers are enjoying buoyant
export orders and increases in output.
The CBI also warned, in its latest economic forecast, that too aggressive
tax cuts before the next general election might, if combined with a fall in
sterling, threaten the government's inflation target.
The government's aim is to keep underlying inflation (excluding mortgage
interest payments) within the lower half of the 1 per cent to 4 per cent
target band.
However, the CBI's model says the target will be missed if Pounds 4bn of tax
cuts in 1996 is combined with a 5 per cent decline in sterling.
Without tax cuts, the CBI forecasts the target will be met, on the
assumption that base rates rise by 1 3/4 percentage points - to 7.5 per cent
 -by 1996. The first rise - of half a percentage point - is likely to occur
in the first quarter of next year.
Ms Kate Barker, the CBI's chief economist, said the organisation 'would
support interest rate rises of around this size', because it believed the
government should meet its inflation target.
The CBI forecasts that economic growth, which was likely to be around 3.9
per cent (allowing for the recently revised third-quarter data) this year,
would fall to 2.8 per cent next year and in 1996.
The recovery will be rebalanced away from consumption and towards exports
and investment.
Today's monthly survey found that 30 per cent of manufacturers planned to
increase prices over the next four months, while only 8 per cent planned to
reduce them.
This positive balance of 22 percentage points was up from 20 points in
October and 15 points in September, and was the highest figure since January
1991.
However, Mr Sudhir Junankar, the CBI's associate economic director, said
that manufacturers had frequently not been able to raise prices in line with
expectations.
In addition, price expectations might be particularly high at the moment
because of the forthcoming January list increases.
The CBI survey also found that export orders were at the strongest level
since March 1988, and that total orders were at their highest since March
1989.
The balance of those reporting an increase in export orders was 10
percentage points, compared with a negative balance of 2 points in October.
The balance of those reporting higher output increased to 21 percentage
points in November, from 19 points, having fallen in each of the past two
months.
</TEXT>
<XX>
