<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Rail chairman with points to prove
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Even a company with as solid an asset portfolio as Railtrack will be judged
ultimately on the quality of its management rather than the elegance of its
Victorian stations or the robustness of its viaducts.
In Mr Robert Horton, its chairman, Railtrack has a leader with a
well-charted career history. He spent 35 years climbing to the top at
British Petroleum only to be ousted in 1992 when a tough cost-cutting
programme failed to reverse declining profits.
Barely installed at Railtrack, he was confronted with a signal workers'
strike and the first public test of his management skills. For someone long
used to operating in a highly regulated industry such as oil, Mr Horton's
performance before a Commons employment committee considering the dispute
was surprisingly uncertain.
His offer to donate to charity the difference between his Pounds 120,000
salary and the Pounds 46,000 earned by Mr Jimmy Knapp, general secretary of
the RMT transport union, if it would resolve the dispute served only to
demonstrate a bizarre sense of the theatrical.
For all his long experience of big company management and his enthusiasm for
the railway, Mr Horton is a newcomer to the business. Industry expertise at
a senior level is provided by Mr John Edmonds, Railtrack chief executive and
a railway man for 34 years.
Under senior management comes a clutch of directorates for areas such as
civil engineering and procurement as well as 10 zonal or regional directors.
Railtrack's literature makes much of the zonal structure although some train
operators say important decisions are referred to head office. They also
accuse Railtrack of arrogance in its dealings with them.
It will clearly be difficult for such a large monopoly player in the new
railway industry to be loved by its smaller partners. Few doubt Mr Horton's
ability to run a tight ship - but management might give some priority to
polishing a somewhat tarnished image.
</TEXT>
