<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / MP's bill to target proceeds of crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir John Hannam, Conservative MP for Exeter, is expected to introduce a bill
giving the courts powers to confiscate assets built up through criminal
activities - after coming third in the annual ballot for private members'
bills.
Speaking after the ballot yesterday, Sir John said he was 'minded' to adopt
what will be widely regarded as an off-the-peg bill provided by the Home
Office. If he goes ahead with the measure there is little doubt that it will
secure widespread support.
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, has already promised that his
department will provide 'every help' in drafting the measure.
The bill would ensure that when people have engaged in a series of crimes,
the courts will be able to assume that all the property that has passed
through the criminal's hands in the previous six years came from crime. They
will be empowered to confiscate its value.
The bill will also prevent the defendant from frustrating a confiscation
order by serving a term of imprisonment in default.
Mrs Diana Maddock, Liberal Democrat MP for Christchurch, who came first in
the ballot, may introduce an energy conservation bill targeted at domestic
premises.
Mr David Jamieson, Labour MP for Devonport, who came second, plans to
introduce a measure imposing more stringent safety standards on outdoor
adventure centres which provide canoeing and other sporting activities for
schools.
</TEXT>
