The Commons public accounts committee yesterday criticised Scottish Homes
for failing to secure the best price for more than 1,000 properties it sold
to a housing trust in the Borders region.
The cross-party committee of MPs attacked state-owned Scottish Homes for
accepting, in 1992, a Pounds 5.8m bid from Waverley Housing, an independent
trust, for the 1,191 houses, over a higher bid of Pounds 6.3m.
The MPs also criticised Scottish Homes for failing to ensure proper
competition in the sale and for awarding Waverley the contract to manage the
houses.
The management contract was awarded to Waverley, without competition, in
February 1989, even though the trust had only been established two months
earlier and an experienced housing association was also interested.
The MPs expressed concern that no records were kept of six meetings in 1987
and 1988 between Scottish Office officials and individuals who later
established Waverley, saying this was 'very unusual'.
Waverley's management costs were more than double previous bills.
Costs for managing 1,800 Borders houses had come to about Pounds 1.2m in
three years before the contract was awarded to Waverley.
But the bill then rose to Pounds 2.4m over three years for Waverley's
management of only 1,300 homes.
</TEXT>
