<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Fatal work accidents lowest ever
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fatal accidents at work are at a record low level, the Health and Safety
Commission (HSC) said yesterday.
Provisional figures in the HSC annual report for 1993-94 said that 379
people were killed at work during the year, compared with 452 in 1992-93.
Recorded injuries which caused three or more days' absence from work fell by
over 8,000 to 134,000 - but the real figure, including unreported accidents,
is believed to be three times greater, which Mr Frank Davies, HSC chairman,
said was 'disgracefully high'.
Mr Davies said the UK had been free of large injury accidents in recent
years though there had been a few 'near big ones', including a fire in
February at Associated Octel in Ellesmere Port, Cheshire, and an explosion
at Texaco's refinery in Milford Haven in July.
Welcoming the accident reductions, the Trades Union Congress calculated that
HSE measures could have saved the economy more than Pounds 200m last year,
including Pounds 70.5m in output because of a reduction in the number of
reportable injuries.
Mr John Rimington, director general of the HSE, highlighted
asbestosis-related diseases which, he said, were causing three times as many
deaths as workplace accidents every year.
He said: 'Demolition and construction workers are still exposed to this
fibre which is one of the biggest killers in society.'
The number of people claiming compensation for occupational asbestosis, he
said, had increased threefold since 1981 and would continue to rise.
He added: 'Thousands of tonnes of asbestos insulation and board remain in
buildings. It is not easily identified.' The HSE, he said, was planning an
asbestos awareness campaign within the construction industry in the New
Year.
Health and Safety Commission Annual Report 1993-94, available from HSE
books, PO Box 1999, Sudbury, Suffolk CO10 6FSD, price Pounds 11, statistical
supplement, price Pounds 9.
</TEXT>
