<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / SIB aids clients of Knight Williams
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Securities and Investments Board, the chief City watchdog, has agreed to
become closely involved in monitoring complaints against Knight Williams,
one of the UK's largest independent financial advisers.
The new complaints procedure offers Knight Williams' clients an alternative
to the existing system. The firm has agreed to analyse each complaint
brought, including those already rejected or failed at arbitration.
Personal interviews between the complainant and a Knight Williams employee
will be recorded for SIB's benefit. If an investor does not want to talk to
the firm, SIB will pay for a third party - Ernst &amp; Young, chartered
accountants - to interview them instead.
SIB will inform Knight Williams of cases where it believes the firm's
handling of the complaint falls short of regulatory standards.
Complaints against an independent adviser are normally handled by the firm
involved and then by Fimbra, its self-regulatory body. SIB confirmed
yesterday that it was 'fairly unusual' for it to be involved so closely in
the complaints procedure of a member of another body, but said it was partly
as a result of Fimbra staffing shortages.
Fimbra closed for new business at the end of September in the wake of the
creation of the Personal Investment Authority, the new watchdog to protect
the private investor.
Mr Kenneth Jordan, chairman of the Knight Williams Investors Action Group,
said the new procedure indicated there were problems for small investors
wishing to complain against an independent adviser. 'However, now is the
opportunity for these problems to be resolved on the basis of reconciliation
and mutual trust,' he said.
Knight Williams attracted considerable publicity when MPs, including Sir
David Steel, former Liberal leader, tabled an early-day motion voicing
concern at the number of complaints against the firm. It was fined Pounds
50,000 by Fimbra in August for breaching 10 Fimbra rules, including issuing
misleading advertisements and failing to maintain proper client records.
Knight Williams said it welcomed the SIB move 'unreservedly'. Its
application to become a member of the PIA, lodged in April, has still not
been processed but it can continue to conduct business until the end of
September next year when SIB's recognition of Fimbra terminates.
</TEXT>
