<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Marketmakers urged to lift veil of secrecy: Norma Cohen on
the debate over rules which allow delays in publication of share prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In financial markets, information is money. So it is not surprising that the
question of who has access to information and when has become the subject of
emotive debate in the City.
Yesterday the Office of Fair Trading released a study concluding that Stock
Exchange rules which allow marketmakers to delay publication of the prices
at which they bought or sold securities are inherently anti-competitive.
At the heart of the debate, regulators and City officials say, is the future
of the market-making system through which Pounds 564bn worth of shares
changed hands last year. Marketmakers are securities firms which, using
their own capital, agree to buy and sell large parcels of shares through all
market conditions.
They say their system, which provides liquidity for institutional investors,
cannot continue unless it is profitable. And if all business becomes public
as soon as it is transacted, it will not be profitable.
They argue that unless such large share trading remains partly opaque,
London will be forced to adopt the order-matching system in which bargains
between buyers and sellers are matched with each other in terms of quantity
and price - as is the case in most European markets. This, they argue, is a
bad deal for shareholders because it reduces liquidity, and London's
standing as an international financial centre will suffer.
Leading institutional investors, who rely on the system, have generally
supported the marketmakers. Mr Geoff Lindey, chairman of the investment
committee of the National Association of Pension Funds, the UK's largest
shareholder group, said: 'We value both liquidity and transparency but if we
had to value one over the other, we would prefer to maintain liquidity.'
He conceded that lack of transparency had some drawbacks. For one thing, it
has made it difficult to price accurately increasingly important equity
derivatives which depend on accurate information about share trading in cash
markets. Also, it is difficult to execute 'programme trades' for large
baskets of shares because doing so requires 'freezing' the price of each
stock at the same point in the day. 'You may be freezing the stock at the
wrong price,' he said.
All these concerns have weighed on the minds of regulators in considering
how to direct the debate about transparency in trading. While anxious not to
unravel the market-making system which has proved so successful in making
London the world's centre for international share trading, they are
concerned that changes in the way share trading is executed around the world
will force changes in London.
The exchange has largely taken the views of its big market-making members to
heart. To buttress its point, it has commissioned a study by consultants
Oliver Wyman - which it has not yet released - that concludes that
marketmakers already suffer big losses on their largest trades.
For trades which are 30 to 50 times normal market size - the average size of
deals in that share for the previous 12 months - marketmakers lose roughly
61 per cent of the capital they place at risk.
That is because marketmakers - or indeed investors - adjust the prices they
subsequently offer for the same security to reflect the most recent trade.
The actual price at which shares in a particular company last traded hands
has real monetary value.
Mr Michael Marks, chief executive at Smith New Court, one of London's
biggest marketmakers, said recently: 'I believe we need marginally less
transparency, not more.'
The OFT has a different view. It has concluded that investors get a bad deal
because marketmakers offering to buy or sell their shares do so at a wider
'spread' between the buy and sell prices than they otherwise might. This
spread can represent profit to the marketmaker. Because they know they are
ignorant of their competitors' deals, marketmakers could be making wider
spreads than they would otherwise in order to account for the uncertainty.
'Public information is generally available in the market, while private
information is known to only one or more market participants,' the OFT
report noted. 'It is private information which allows particular traders to
gain at the expense of others.'
Marketmakers who agree to buy a large line of stock from an institutional
investor are likely to witness an immediate marking down of that share by
other market participants as soon as the sale becomes public knowledge.
It was this practice in the years after Big Bang in 1986, when all big
trades had to be reported immediately, that led to swingeing losses for
marketmakers.
In response, the exchange decided to allow members to delay trade
publication. Current rules allow publication of any transaction at least
three times the normal market size of any stock to be delayed for 90 minutes
while the marketmaker hedges his position against a sharp price reaction.
Moreover, any trade 75 times normal market size may be delayed for up to
five days or until the transaction is hedged.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
