<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Industry welcomes contaminated land plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBYN CHALMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday unveiled proposals to deal with contaminated land
based on a suitable-use approach which has been broadly welcomed by
industry.
The approach requires remedial action only where the contamination poses a
risk to health or the environment and there are appropriate and
cost-effective methods of doing so. This will significantly reduce the cost
to industry of cleaning up sites and moves decisively away from the hardline
US policy of strict liability.
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, said in a written parliamentary
answer that the proposed Environment Agency should take over research work
and guidance on contaminated land now being carried out by the Department of
the Environment.
He added that legislative amendments to the provisions would be proposed to
enable regulators - the Environment Agency and local authories - to require
the prevention or abatement of contamination.
One move which was applauded by industry groups was the decision to repeal
section 143 of the Environment Protection Act 1990. This proposed that
district councils should maintain publicly available registers of all
contaminated sites.
Mr Gummer said that the regulatory authorities would have the task of
identifying problems caused by contamination. They would keep a register of
all significantly polluted sites in their area, recording actual rather than
suspected contamination.
He added that the government did not consider that a general register of
land subject to potentially contaminative uses was warranted.
The government will also propose legislative amendments to remove statutory
exemptions for abandoned mines where escaping water pollutes controlled
waters. Mine operators will have to give the agency six months notice of any
proposed abandonment.
During formal and informal talks held by the government, financial
institutions had expressed concerns that they might be held liable for
pollution caused by their clients, and Mr Gummer made the assurance that
they would not be subject to open-ended liabilities.
Mr Tim Sweeney, director-general of the British Bankers' Association,
welcomed government conclusions that the act of lending did not of itself
open the lender to liability.
The proposals were generally welcomed for ending the uncertainty that
business and the property industry had faced.
The Confederation of British Industry said it believed the framework would
help encourage investment in the development of contaminated land, bringing
more land back into use and reducing the pressure on green-field sites.
However, the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors warned that
clarification of a number of key elements would be crucial to the success of
the proposals. These included the degree of flexibility local authorities
would have in implementing their new duties and what standard of clean-up
would be required.
</TEXT>
