<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / 'Where have you British been all these years . . .'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, WILLIAM LEWIS and JAMES WHITTINGTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In August a group of British businessmen spent 14 uncomfortable hours
crossing the desert of Iraq's Al Nafar province from Jordan. Their
destination was Baghdad. Because of UN sanctions there are no direct flights
from Europe to the Iraqi capital but, against advice from the Foreign
Office, they were willing to brave dust, heat and possible kidnapping. The
prize was a chance to return to what, before the Gulf War, had been a
lucrative market of Pounds 800m a year
In spite of the government's public support for the continuation of
sanctions against Iraq some British companies are preparing to resume trade
with President Saddam Hussein's regime when they are lifted.
On Sunday, 17 British water treatment and engineering companies will begin
exhibiting at the Baghdad Trade Fair Centre.
The British organisers of the fair - billed as covering humanitarian aid -
say it has been cleared by the United Nations sanctions committee.
Communication licences have been obtained from the Department of Trade and
Industry, allowing participating companies to talk to the Iraqis about
medical and water treatment and sewage products.
The companies on the August trade trip had also been issued with
communication licences by the DTI. They talked to senior Iraqi ministers who
in turn arranged meetings with the heads of state-owned companies.
Among the businessmen who travelled across the desert was Mr Christopher
Doherty, managing director of United Projects, a trading company. Before the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in August 1990, his company was exporting up to
Pounds 15m of goods a year to Iraq, including agricultural machinery and
pharmaceutical products.
Mr Doherty this week recalled: 'We went to reassure the Iraqis that we
wanted to re-establish business. When we got there the Iraqis asked us:
'Where have you British been all these years?''
Others in the delegation included representatives of Binnie &amp; Partners,
engineering consultants, and Thames Water. The two companies were exploring
the possibility of restarting an abandoned water treatment plant they helped
build.
Mr James Hetherington, a director of Binnie &amp; Partners, said he agreed to
join the delegation because it opened up the possibility of broadening
commercial contacts with the Iraqis. 'I told the Iraqis we would like to
repair the existing plant and in due course get more contracts.'
Mr Ewan Drummond, business director with Johnson &amp; Johnson, a supplier of
medical products which was involved in the August trip, said his company was
hoping to win Iraqi contracts after sanctions were lifted. 'It is quite
clear that the DTI was involved with the visit to Iraq,' he said. 'It was
not an officially sponsored trip, but nor did the DTI disapprove. We always
seek advice from the DTI to make sure that we comply with the sanctions
regime.'
Mr Ian Detheridge, financial director of Wright Rain, a water irrigation
company, said: 'We were interested originally because we were told
humanitarian aid was permissible and we wanted to sell the Iraqis irrigation
equipment . . . but when we got to Baghdad we realised that the Iraqis'
intention was to see the restoration of trade ties (with) the UK.'
The trade visit was organised by a commercial lobby group called the Iraqi
British Interest Group (IBI). It is also organising a trip in January for
the vehicle and construction trades. Member companies pay annual
subscriptions of between Pounds 250 and Pounds 500.
The IBI describes itself as a 'strategic association'. Its main organiser,
Mr Stephen Crouch, a business consultant, said its aim was 'to bring
together intelligence on the Iraqi market to see how we can move in when
conditions are better'. He added: 'Industry is very sensitive about being
seen to have contact with the Iraqi regime. However, companies obviously
want to maintain contact with the Iraqi state and to see what the country
requires.'
According to Mr Doherty, one of the group's strongest supporters is Mr Henry
Bellingham, a Conservative MP who is parliamentary private secretary to Mr
Malcolm Rifkind, the defence minister. 'Mr Bellingham is fully supportive of
what we are doing,' he said.
Mr Doherty says Mr Bellingham was promoting British commercial links with
Iraq when he met Iraqi officials in Amman in early September.
When approached this week, Mr Bellingham said he had 'no regular contacts
with IBI', and added that his contacts with the Iraqis were informal.
Commercial support for the IBI has been growing. Some 100 companies from a
range of sectors including pharmaceuticals, financial services,
construction, and transport have expressed an interest in resuming ties with
Iraq.
One Whitehall official said Mr Crouch's objectives were 'a bit more loose
than Her Majesty's Government's'. Mr Crouch insists he has British interests
at the heart of his campaign.
Companies which have signalled their intention to go to Iraq in January
include Leyland Trucks, crane and construction equipment maker RB
International and fire engine maker Angus Fires.
Leyland said: 'When sanctions are lifted there is clearly going to be
opportunities for new business. Our feeling is that our competitors are
already preparing themselves.'
UK companies fear that European competitors have been moving faster than
they have. Trade delegations from France, Spain, Germany and Italy have
visited Baghdad during recent months.
Mr Andrew Brown, a senior manager with RB International, said last week:
'When sanctions are lifted, the whole place is going to come alive in trade
terms. We want to be there when that happens.'
</TEXT>
