<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Investment guide for regeneration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBYN CHALMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Development projects which create jobs, promote inward investment and
strengthen local economies will be given priority treatment by English
Partnerships, the government agency, according to its investment guide
published today.
English Partnerships was created earlier this year to co-ordinate urban
regeneration policy and encourage development partnerships with the private,
public and voluntary sectors.
The investment guide says the agency will focus on physical regeneration
initiatives which show a significant return in terms of jobs created, inward
investment attracted and the provision of new housing and employment space.
The guide goes on: 'In considering environmental projects, we will
concentrate on those which are urgently required for health and safety
reasons and form part of a wider strategy of development and reclamation.'
While the agency was able to operate on vacant, derelict and contaminated
land throughout England it would concentrate on areas where mines have been
closed, City Challenge and other inner-city areas, and rural regions with
severe economic need.
Lord Walker, chairman of English Partnerships, said the agency was committed
to the creation of innovative development packages with a wide variety of
partners to bring benefits to local communities, existing industry and
inward investors.
He said: 'With the help of this comprehensive guide, our partners can help
make this objective a reality.'
