<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Law to offer protection for disabled workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Disabled people will be protected against discrimination at work under
long-awaited legislation, the government announced yesterday.
Mr William Hague, minister for the disabled, told the Commons it will be
unlawful for an employer to treat a disabled person less favourably than
others unless there are 'justifiable reasons'. He said the proposals
represented the greatest advance for disabled people in the history of the
country. But Labour said they did not go far enough.
Mr Hague refused to say how much the proposals would cost industry. He said
a full compliance-cost assessment will be produced alongside the bill when
it is published before the end of the year.
The Department of Social Security said the costs to business would be well
below the estimated Pounds 17bn cost of implementing the private member's
bill for the disabled proposed earlier this year by Mr Roger Berry, Labour
MP for Kingswood.
One official said the proposals could cost employers about Pounds 50m a year
for the next 15 years. Ministers are examining ways of ensuring that no
company will pay adjustment costs above a specified percentage of their
profits.
The Confederation of British Industry said it was important the measures
would not be 'unnecessarily costly to business'. The Institute of Directors
said the statement contained 'open-ended commitments which could prove very
costly'.
Mr Hague said employers will have to make 'a reasonable adjustment where
that would help overcome the practical effects of disability'. But he added
that regulations would 'ensure adjustments do not involve excessive costs'.
Employers with 20 or fewer workers will be exempt from the legislation.
The government also intends to abolish the quota scheme that requires
employers with 20 or more employees to employ at least 3 per cent of
registered disabled people. It believes the scheme is unworkable and fails
to meet the needs of the disabled.
A National Disability Council is to be created to advise the government. Mr
Hague said: 'This will be a new, powerful voice for disabled people in the
decision-making process.'
But the new body was criticised for not being strong enough.
Employers 'where practical' will have to remove physical and communication
barriers preventing access by the disabled to goods and services. But Mr
Hague said employers will have to make modifications 'only to the extent
they are readily achievable and subject to a financial limit'. Financial
services are to be included in the new statutory right of equal access.
</TEXT>
