<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / MPs back 4.7% ministerial pay rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs last night voted by a large majority to give ministers a 4.7 per cent
pay increase next year, in spite of the opposition of the Labour leader and
prominent unionists.
Amid growing controversy about recent increases in the salaries of top
executives, MPs approved the government's recommended pay rise, which is
about 2.3 per cent above the level of inflation.
At the end of a debate forced by Labour MPs, the Commons voted by 179 to 13
in favour of the rise, a government majority of 166. Mr Tony Newton, the
leader of the Commons, defended the increase, saying it made up for earlier
freezes.
Opening a debate on the pay award, he said that MPs had lost about Pounds
2,000 each and ministers up to Pounds 4,000 each because of a salary freeze
over the last two years. 'That money has gone for good,' he insisted. 'It's
not something made up. It is a permanent loss.'
However, Labour MPs condemned the proposals, saying they were unacceptable
when public-sector workers were being asked to accept pay restraint.
Mr Dennis Skinner, Labour MP for Bolsover, said the increase would 'stick in
the gullet' of the public.
Another Labour MP, Mr Jeff Rooker, claimed that it was 'demeaning' for the
Commons to debate such proposals.
Ministers were worth their pay in ultimate responsibility, but not in terms
of their productivity which had been 'absolutely pathetic', he added.
According to figures released by the government yesterday, the increase will
boost the prime minister's salary from Pounds 78,292 to Pounds 82,003 at the
start of next year. A cabinet minister's salary will rise to about Pounds
67,000, an increase of about Pounds 3,000.
Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, could claim a rise pushing his salary up
to Pounds 64,255. However, he has made clear that he will not accept the
rise 'when millions of others are having no increase at all'.
Mr Alan Duncan, the Tory MP for Rutland and Melton, branded Mr Blair's
decision not to take a rise as 'an opportunistic stunt'. He said the Labour
leader had one policy, 'and that policy is to feed discontent and then to
milk it for all it's worth'.
Mr Duncan added: 'He is choosing to seize on grievance and cash in on the
politics of what I call the lowest common denominator.'
Earlier this week, Mr John Major faced fierce questions about the 75 per
cent salary increase recently awarded to Mr Cedric Brown, the chief
executive of British Gas.
At the same time, senior unionists have attacked the increase. Mr John
Monks, the TUC general secretary, has said that the rise would make the
government's public-sector pay freeze 'even more unsustainable'.
</TEXT>
