<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Nerves on edge for the battle of amendments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The corridors of the Commons were yesterday buzzing with speculation about
the outcome of Monday's vote on the European Union finance bill.
But as government whips anxiously counted and recounted their lists of loyal
backbenchers, it became clear that the government's future rests on the
willingness of Tory rebels to vote for a Labour amendment.
Mr Bill Cash, a leading Eurosceptic Tory backbencher, sought to set the
agenda early in the day by drafting an amendment giving the Commons public
accounts committee powers to block Britain's EU contributions.
The amendment reads: 'This house has confidence in Her Majesty's Government,
but declines to give a second reading to the bill unless HMG gives an
undertaking to the House of Commons that no money should be paid to the EC
in any year under the own resources decision . . . unless and until the PAC
of this House declares in that year that it is satisfied with the
effectiveness of the new procedures for detecting and dealing with fraud in
the EC.'
The Eurosceptics know that the amendment is unacceptable to the government
because it would set up a mechanism making it impossible for the government
to give the EU guarantees that payments would be made when they become due.
But under the arcane rules of the Commons, that did not matter to the
Eurosceptics, because they know that the amendment will never be selected
for debate by Mrs Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker.
The intention was twofold: to make the Eurosceptic view crystal clear; and
to provide an opportunity for Labour to maximise the potential vote against
the government by adopting the rebels' tone and language.
In the event, Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, tabled a toughly worded
motion deploring fraud and waste, but couched in terms that make it unlikely
that most of the rebels will dare to support it.
When MPs decide at about 10pm on Monday, Labour's amendment will be voted on
first. If it succeeds, it would delay implementation of the increased
contributions until 1996 because no bill can be tabled twice in one year.
That, however, would be academic because the success of the amendment would
be regarded as a government defeat on an issue of confidence, prompting an
immediate request by Mr John Major for a dissolution of parliament and a
general election.
It is more likely that the amendment will be defeated, and there would then
be a vote on the second reading of the bill - approving the principle of the
legislation. The division would be a sham because the failure of the
amendment would have shown that the rebels were not prepared to defeat the
government.
If that happens, Labour says it would abstain. Other parties might follow
suit, presenting the government with a resounding victory.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
