<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 94 / Serbs press into Bihac as Nato squabbles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, BRUCE CLARK, LONDON AND AGENCIES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serb forces pressed their military offensive into the embattled town
of Bihac late yesterday as squabbling Nato countries tried to put together a
plan to save the battered enclave in north-west Bosnia.
The United Nations commander in Bosnia, General Sir Michael Rose, accused
the Bosnian Serbs of 'flagrant and blatant' violation of the 'safe area'
designated by the UN at Bihac.
He said the Bosnian Serbs 'certainly have crossed the line beyond which the
safety of the population of Bihac is now threatened' and had refused a
ceasefire. 'This is a very grave development which we have to act upon,' he
said.
Gen Rose unsuccessfully negotiated with Bosnian Serb leaders in Pale, near
Sarajevo, while ambassadors from Nato's 16 member countries became bogged
down in unexpectedly tough talks in Brussels. The ambassadors failed to
agree on details of a blueprint to halt the Serb advance on Bihac, referring
the matter to the UN for assessment.
Mr Robert Hunter, US ambassador to Nato, said the allies were in broad
agreement over a proposal to set up a 'stabilisation zone' around Bihac, but
some details would have to be worked out by the UN.
The US expects the proposal to go to military specialists at the UN rather
than the Security Council. The specialists are expected to assess what
troops might be needed to make the proposal work.
The US initially urged its allies to create, around Bihac, as wide a zone as
possible where heavy weapons would be subject to air strikes. But European
members of Nato, led by France, suggested a more modest plan for a four-mile
extension of the existing 'safe area', within which the UN is committed to
protecting civilians and its own peacekeepers.
The French also insisted that more ground troops would be needed to
implement any ceasefire agreement. The French stance was aimed at driving
home to the US, which has declined to send ground troops to Bosnia, the
limits of a policy based purely on air power.
Gen Rose said that Bosnian Serbs late yesterday advanced from high ground to
the very outskirts of Bihac. He did not think the town could hold out
against any sustained attack.
An amateur radio operator reporting from Bihac said the Bosnian Serbs were
only one kilometre from the town centre.
In Moscow, Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, sharply
criticised the Bosnian government, accusing it of provoking the fighting
around Bihac in the hope of prompting western intervention. There could be
no military solution to the Bosnian conflict and outside intervention could
result in a 'second Afghanistan or Vietnam'.
Mr Kozyrev said next week's meeting of the contact group - the US, Russia,
Britain, France and Germany - must send a 'clear signal that the world
community . . . favours a return to political methods' in Bosnia. Mr John
Major, the prime minister, last night warned that the UN might have to pull
out of Bosnia if there were a resumption of all-out war in the region. Mr
Major said there could be no prospect of imposing peace on Bosnia through
aerial bombardment.
He said that he had sent a letter to leaders of contact group countries
stressing 'the urgency of progress' at their next meeting.
The UN's contingent in Bihac is largely made up of 1,200 poorly armed
Bangladeshis, who were resupplied by a UN convoy yesterday under an
agreement with the Serbs.
The UN's vulnerability to any all-out confrontation with the Serbs was
driven home yesterday when over 250 peacekeepers from Canada, France, Russia
and Ukraine were detained in the Sarajevo area.
Allies fall out, Page 2
</TEXT>
